Turner (2014) writes in the BJOG:

The abortion scene in Nauru is marked by a high level of ‘medicalised’ abortion services, with surgical abortion the norm. The level of surgical provision might potentially contribute to hospital requests as women prefer to have a surgeon who is familiar with the surgical management of abortion, anywhere from a clean table, till, or operating theatre to an operating room with a full crash cart and available induced clinical midwife and anesthetist. Governments’ solicitation of overseas and local abortion clinicians is one reason why the practice has become normalised and familiar on the island […] By using its small population as an excuse to order a vastly disproportionate number of abortion clinicians, the Nauru government reduces the risk to other women seeking abortion on the mainland. As one doctor commented: ‘Every single woman who travels who has an abortion by us either returns to Nauru at their own expense […] or stays back’. The presence of specialist doctors on the island alleviates fears that incompetent medical staff might cause long-term harm to women seeking abortion on the island through surgical mishaps’.
